```

### DynamicAspectLoader.java

This is the class that manages the dynamic loading of aspects:

```java
package com.example.aop.aspect;

import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.condition.ConditionalOnProperty;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;

@Configuration
@ConditionalOnProperty(name = "enable.logging", havingValue = "true")
public class DynamicAspectLoader {

    @Autowired
    private LoggingAspect loggingAspect;

    @Bean
    public LoggingAspect loggingAspectBean() {
        return loggingAspect;
    }
}
```

### Application Properties

Add the following property to `application.properties`:

```properties
enable.logging=true
```

### Running the Application

When you run the application, the `LoggingAspect` will be loaded because the `enable.logging` property is set to `true`. If you change the property to `false`, the aspect will be unloaded.

### Conclusion

By leveraging Spring's powerful AOP capabilities and dynamic configuration, we can create a flexible and hot-swappable AOP system. This approach allows you to manage cross-cutting concerns like logging, security, and performance monitoring without restarting your application. The key takeaway is to use conditional annotations and dynamic configuration to enable or disable aspects based on runtime properties.

